Despite increasing availability of computer science (CS) coursework in U.S. high schools over the last five years, gaps in access and success for students from traditionally underrepresented groups remain. One approach to increasing student interest and success in CS involves providing all students opportunities to develop foundational computational thinking (CT) skills through integrating CT into secondary school curriculum. We developed a program that embeds CT skills instruction in core subject matter courses taken by all 9th- and 10th-grade students. The program comprises a series of instructional modules—each including two to five lessons—delivered throughout the school year. The modules are designed to support students to develop and apply CT skills (such as pattern recognition) and coding skills to learn subject matter concepts. We prepared subject matter teachers—many of whom had limited CS experience—to deliver the modules. Across three school years, we implemented the program in nine Uncommon Schools public charter high schools serving primarily Black and Latinx students from economically disadvantaged backgrounds. This poster presents findings from an implementation evaluation examining students' and teachers' experiences with the program and discusses implications of those findings for future efforts to develop, implement, and sustain CT skills programs integrated into subject matter courses for high school students. We include takeaways for (1) developing and delivering CT skills instruction, (2) preparing subject matter teachers to teach CT skills, and (3) implementing and sustaining CT skills programs.